entry.title: cros_next: add MaterialNext dialog (part 2)
entry.content:
This cl follows crrev.com/c/4500464 to implement the auto

adjustment of dialog sizes.



The cl adds a class called SystemDialog to create the dialog

widget parented to a host window and adjust the widget size

according to the host window size.



The resizing rules of the dialog are as follows:

- when host width > 672, dialog width = 512.

- when 520 < host width < 671, dialog width decreases with a

padding of 80 on both sides.

- when 424 < host width < 519, dialog width = 359.

- when 400 < host width < 423, dialog width decreases with a

padding of 32 on both sides.

- when host width < 399, dialog width = 296.



The final effecs are shown in the bug comments.

entry.title: shortcuts: Add ShortcutCustomizationOverride pref
entry.content:
Implements a user pref that stores the user's shortcut

customizations. This iteration will apply only RemoveAccelerator()

states.



Pref storage explanation:

Customization overrides are stored as deltas from the default system

accelerators. If an accelerator is added, the pref is populated with

an entry of the {action ID: {Accelerator, ModificationAction}}.

`ModificationAction` indicates whether the accelerator was `kAdd`

or `kRemove`. Note that `kRemove` refers to removing/disabling a

default accelerator.



Applying the pref override:

For each action ID in the pref storage, iterate through the list of

overrides and apply the modifications. For example:

{TOGGLE_CALENDAR: [{Accelerator(VKEY_A, EF_COMMAND_DOWN), kAdd}]}

Will invoke: `AddAccelerator(TOGGLE_CALENDAR,

Accelerator(VKEY_A,EF_COMMAND_DOWN))`



Any implicit removes, as part of a conflict resolution, is not stored.



An additional validation check is performed after applying the pref

overrides to ensure correctness of the accelerator mappings. If failed,

the accelerators are reset to the system default as a fail safe.

entry.title: Update GPU.MultipleSwapsDelta when frame production is off
entry.content:
We are currently enqueuing more than 10 presented frames in

CompositorFrameReportingController::TrackSwapTiming before we are seeing

a WillBeginImplFrame, where we calculate and emit the metric.



The metric is not overflowing, so we aren't dealing with multiple swaps

incorrectly being accumulated across multiple VSync intervals. So we

must be dropped a lot of old presentations.



This change updates to clear the queue of presentations when we turn off

needing begin frames. While also blocking enqueuing presentations while

in this state.



In some configurations the delivery of DidPresentCompositorFrame can be

quite late. So we are likely running into these being enqueued. This

change also doesn't enqueue presentations older than the current

BeginFrameArgs, as they would just be removed at calculation time

anyways.

entry.title: Use normal `configs` defaults and settings for rust GN targets
entry.content:
The rust_target() template needs to know multiple types of configs

since it can generate multiple types of targets (library + unit test).

But other rust targets like rust_executable, rust_static_library,

rust_shared_library, rust_macro do not. Set their default configs

the way other GN templates do, with something like:



set_defaults("rust_static_library") {

configs = default_compiler_configs

}



Then give the `configs` to rust_target() in each template through

rust_targets's multiple channels (executable_configs, etc).

rust_target can assert() that it is given configs it needs for the

type of target it is building.



Instead of having cargo_crate() go through rust_target() directly,

have it use the rust_executable(), rust_static_library() and

rust_macro() templates so that it acts through the same code

paths. Since cargo_crate() builds multiple things, like rust_target()

it needs multiple config inputs, so it uses library_configs,

proc_macro_configs and executable_configs. These get forwarded to

the templates as their `configs`.



Then rust_target no longer needs default configs, as its always an

impl detail of rust_executable, etc. And those things always provide

configs.



R=adetaylor@chromium.org

entry.title: speculation rules: Ensure invalidation sets are up to date before any possible DOM mutation.
entry.content:
If an element has its style valid, and then a document rule is added,

and then the document changes in such a way that the document rule

contains a selector that newly matches _before_ style is made clean

(e.g., immediately), it is currently possible for this to be missed

because the CSSGlobalRuleSet has not yet updated its features but is

nonetheless used to evaluate what needs to be dirtied.



This addresses it by updating that, and its prerequisites, immediately

when the document rules selectors are changed. This doesn't force all of

style computation -- just enough to be able to invalidate accurately.

entry.title: Fix Rust linking on component and debug Windows builds
entry.content:
1. The CRT can be specified from rustc but only static/dynamic,

not release/debug. This is tracked upstream in

https://github.com/rust-lang/libs-team/issues/211



Because of this, we must not use the CRT command line options

from rustc, and instead specify the library directly. This is

done at the same location where the CRT is chosen for C++

targets via the "/MD" and friends flags.



Then, we must not have rustc try to also link the CRT and we

disable that by setting -Zlink-directives=false for the libc

crate.



2. After the above, we have two sets of libraries that must be

linked when using the rust stdlib.



Internal dependencies, which are #[link] directives from the

libc crate (other than the CRT), which must be linked any time

the rust lib is used.



Public dependencies, which are linked automatically by rustc

but are not linked by C++ targets that depend on Rust targets.



So we split these into two configs, and expose the latter on

the BUILD rule for C++ targets that depend on Rust.



3. The local build of stdlib is here to stay and is always used

with the Chromium toolchain, so remove a bunch of configuration

levers around it and just hardcode the stdlib in when using the

Chromium toolchain. And hardcode the prebuilt stdlib path when

not using the Chromium toolchain. This removes a bunch of

branches elsewhere in our GN rules as we can simply depend on

the "rust stdlib target" instead of choosing between them.



Then drop the test build target that was opting into the local

stdlib as all our Rust build tests do that now.



4. Don't use __attribute__((visibility("default"))) on Windows,

use __declspec(dllexport) instead.



I don't know that this fixes anything, but that attribute doesn't

exist on Windows, so yeah.



5. In the component build, C++ targets are linked with the dynamic

CRT. In order to have mixed targets, Rust needs to as well. Then

Rust build script exes are linked with the dynamic CRT and they are

unable to find the DLL on the bots (which don't have Visual Studio)

installed. The CRT DLL is placed in root_out_dir, so we move build

script exes to the root_out_dir in order to have them find the DLL

and be able to execute.



6. Ensure the CRT DLLs are present on the bots when running the

tests by adding a data_deps edge to them for build_rust_tests.

Normally this edge comes from a dependency on //base which basically

everything has, but our Rust build tests don't.



7. Disable rust_shared_library unit test on Windows component build

while we figure out how to get the right `data_deps` edge from the

test to the library so that it's included in the isolate. When

building a library's tests, the library itself is recompiled under

cfg=test as part of the test exe. So the rlib or shared library

itself is not used. But we still need to depend on any transitive

deps of that library when building the unit tests, so the unit tests

add a deps edge onto the library.



For shared libraries this deps edge doesn't do anything on Linux, or

on Windows non-component builds. But on Windows component builds, the

unit test EXE acquires a dependency on the DLL (as shown by dumpbin)

and thus the DLL needs to be present when running the test.



Bug: 1442273, 1434719

entry.title: Remove origin from AutofillProfile constructor.
entry.content:
The concept of origins is about to be removed from AutofillProfile

entirely. See doc linked in the bug. As a first step, this CL removes

the origin parameter from AutofillProfile's constructor.



In Autofill, the exact value of the origin doesn't matter (anymore). It

is only distinguished between settings and non-settings origin. For this

reason, almost-all non-settings origins are dropped. Settings origins

are kept by an explicit AutofillProfile::set_origin() call.

In a few locations, such as when reading from the database and when

converting between proto <-> AutofillProfile, the values of the origin

are intentionally kept.



Lastly, this CL simplifies some of the constructor calls, since the

default constructor of AutofillProfile already generates a random GUID.



This CL keeps the behavior as-is.



Most of this CL was generated using tools/git/mffr.py and regex like the

following:

Pattern: 'AutofillProfile (\w+)\((\n.*)?base::Uuid::GenerateRandomV4\(\).AsLowercaseString\(\),( |\n.*)kSettingsOrigin\)'

entry.title: [iOS][byot] Update bottom message positioning logic
entry.content:
The visibility of pinned tabs is used to be determined by `self.pinned

TabsViewController.view.hidden`, but now the pinned tabs view controller

is updated to have the `visibility` property and the actual visibility

change of the view controller happens after an animation delay. This

means the positioning of the BYOT bottom message, which used to rely on

`self.pinnedTabsViewController.view.hidden`, is calculated BEFORE the

pinned tab view controller really disappears, and thus its positioning

entry.title: fusebox: escape ADP mount path suffix
entry.content:
This fixes OneDrive ADP + Files app integration for Fusebox code paths.

The Dropbox ADP already worked prior to this commit.



Out of the three CreateExternalFileSystemURL calls in volume_manager.cc,

only ADP (Android Documents Provider) passes a non-empty base::FilePath

final argument. FSP and MTP passes an empty {}.



Escaping makes it consistent with

"arc::GetDocumentsProviderMountPath(authority, document_id)" as called

by Volume::CreateForDocumentsProvider. The OneDrive ADP's document_id is

"pivots/username@example.com" and the "/" needs escaping to "%2F".



Also change the final fragment from the root_id to the document_id.

These are the same for many ADP implementations, but again for OneDrive,

they are different (the root_id is just "username@example.com"). It's

not always obvious which of the two to use. Confusingly, the

arc::GetDocumentsProviderMountPath argument is named "root_document_id".

lazy-loaded images with certain absolute dimension thresholds. These

HTMLImageElement::LazyLoadDimensionType, so all associated code can be

removed. Legacy tests of image load differences based on image

dimensions have also been removed.
